Yenagoa – Bayelsa State Government received an aggregate gross inflow of N30.396 billion from the Federation Account Allocation Committee (FAAC) for the months of February and March, 2018. The total gross federal receipt for February was N15.29 billion while that of March stood at N15.367 billion. Rear Admiral Gboribiogha Jonah, Deputy Governor of the state, disclosed this at the weekend during the transparency briefing for February and March 2018, which was held at the Government House, Yenagoa. He said that the sum of N1.6 billion was deducted at source for each of the two months by the FAAC, making it a total of N3.2 billion. Jonah said that the FAAC deductions left the state with a total net revenue of N27.11 billion with N13.386 billion for February and N13.724 billion for March. He stated that the internally generated revenue (IGR) for January was N1.7 billion while that of February was N1.1 billion. On outflows in February, the deputy governor said that the government spent N1.788 billion for bank loans repayment, civil servants’ salaries N2.969 billion and political appointees’ salaries’ N301.218 million. Others include recurrent payment N3.377 billion, capital payment N4.211 billion, salary grant to state-owned tertiary institutions N630 million, 10 percent contribution to primary school teachers’ salaries, cost of IGR collection N97. 465 and Ban COT charges N144.399 million. For the month of March, Jonah announced that bank loans repayment was N1.808 billion, civil servants’ salaries N2.963 billion, political appointees’ salaries N344.490 million and salary grant to state-owned tertiary institutions N630 million. Others were recurrent expenditure N3.639 billion, capital expenditure N6.286 billion, 10 percent contribution to primary school teachers’ salaries, cost of IGR collection N69.629 million while COT bank charges was N139.37 million. The deputy governor said that balance of funds for February was N9.322 billion while that of March stood at N7.5 billi